dist_tbl <- flights |> # subset the data
  filter(month == 1) |>
  group_by(carrier) |> # another way to select distinct occurrences

    mean_dist = mean(distance, na.rm = TRUE),

3 Question 3

print("Below is the sd and mean distance travelled per carrier:")
[1] "Below is the sd and mean distance travelled per carrier:"
Code 
flights |>
  filter(month == 1) |>
  group_by(carrier) |>
  summarise(
    num_flights = n(), # counts the flights per carrier
    uniq_dist = n_distinct(distance), # counts the unique distances
    mean_dist = mean(distance, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_dist = sd(distance, na.rm = TRUE)
    ) |>
  arrange(num_flights)

3.1 Explanation

Sd measures variability in data. Thus, if all flights for a carrier in month 1 show the same distance, there is no variation in the data and thus the sd will be 0, as is the case with carriers F9, AS, etc. Moreover, if a carrier, such as OO, has 1 or less flights in month 1, then there is no variability to measure and the denominator of the sd formula will be 0, which is why “NA” is returned by R.

  filter(paste(origin, dest) %in% paste(common_routes$origin, common_routes$dest)) |>

#part 3
best_worst_airline_per_route <- avg_arr_delay_by_airline |>
  group_by(origin, dest) |>
  summarise(
    worst_airline = carrier[which.max(avg_arr_delay)], # finds the index of the first max avg arr delay
    best_airline = carrier[which.min(avg_arr_delay)],
    max_delay = max(avg_arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    min_delay = min(avg_arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  )
